	<h3>The Architectural Marvels of Ancient India</h3>
	<p>
		Ancient Indian temples are far more than places of worship; they are monuments of outstanding engineering, art, and scientific achievement. Constructed without modern tools, cranes, or concrete, these stone structures have stood the test of time for centuries, showcasing the advanced knowledge of mathematics, astronomy, and geology possessed by ancient builders.
	</p>
	
	<h3>Geometry and Sacred Alignments</h3>
	<p>
		Most ancient temples are built using complex sacred geometry, aligning precisely with astronomical events. For instance, the Konark Sun Temple is shaped like a giant chariot with wheels that act as precise sundials, showing the exact time of day down to the minute. Many temple layouts are based on the Vastupurusha Mandala, reflecting cosmic order and balance in their geometric proportions.
	</p>
	
	<h3>The Mystery of Monolithic Structures</h3>
	<p>
		One of the most extraordinary achievements of ancient engineering is the Kailash Temple at Ellora. Carved out of a single volcanic basalt rock cliff from top to bottom, builders excavated over 200,000 tons of rock to create a multi-story temple complex. This top-down excavation method left zero room for error, making it one of the greatest architectural wonders in human history.
	</p>
	
	<h3>Acoustic Wonders and Stone Engineering</h3>
	<p>
		Many South Indian temples feature "musical pillars" carved out of solid granite, which resonate with distinct musical notes when tapped gently. This reveals a deep understanding of acoustic engineering and stone density. Every arch, pillar, and sculpture serves a dual purpose—combining structural support with intricate storytelling, celebrating the timeless heritage of India.
	</p>
